        <fr:title text="Injective, Surjective &amp; Bijective (Sets)">Injective, Surjective &amp; Bijective (Sets)</fr:title>
        <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <html:p>A function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : X \to  Y]]></fr:tex> is called <html:strong>injective</html:strong> (or <html:em>one-to-one</html:em>) if for every pair of elements <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_1, x_2 \in  X]]></fr:tex> the following holds:</html:p>
        <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
    f(x_1) = f(x_2) \implies  x_1 = x_2
  ]]></fr:tex>
        <html:p>A function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : X \to  Y]]></fr:tex> is called <html:strong>surjective</html:strong> (or <html:em>onto</html:em>) if for every element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y \in  Y]]></fr:tex> there exists an element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  X]]></fr:tex> such that:</html:p>
        <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
    f(x) = y
  ]]></fr:tex>
        <html:p>A function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : X \to  Y]]></fr:tex> is called <html:strong>bijective</html:strong> if it is both <html:em>injective</html:em> and <html:em>surjective</html:em>. In this case there exists an <html:strong>inverse function</html:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f^{-1} : Y \to  X]]></fr:tex> such that the following hold:</html:p>
        <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
    f^{-1}(f(x)) = x
    \quad 
    f(f^{-1}(y)) = y
  ]]></fr:tex>
        <html:p>In the categorical sense a bijection is just an <html:strong>isomorphism</html:strong> in a 0-category (i.e. the category of sets). We can give an equivalent more pedantic definition of bijectivity as follows:</html:p>
        <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
    \forall  y \in  Y.\ (f(f^{-1}(y)) = y \land  \forall  x \in  X.\ (f(y) = x \to  f^{-1}(x) = y))
  ]]></fr:tex>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
  </fr:mainmatter>
